ch 1202–1257","1197–1248":"1197–1248","1197–Male":"1197–Deceased","1225–Female":"1225–Deceased","1218–Female":"1218–Deceased","1221–Female":"1221–Deceased","1225–1279":"1225–1279","1202–1257":"1202–1257","1248":"1248","1225":"1225","about 1217":"about 1217","1257":"1257","1202":"1202","1279":"1279","1221":"1221","ABT 1225":"about 1225","1197":"1197","15 March 1202":"15 March 1202","1218":"1218","Boufflers, Somme, Picardie, France":"Boufflers, Somme, Picardie, France","Domart-en-Ponthieu, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Domart-en-Ponthieu, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France","Boufflers, 80118, Somme, Picardie, France":"Boufflers, Somme, Picardie, France","Boufflers, Abbeville, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Boufflers, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France","Boufflers, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Boufflers, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Adèle","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."],"variants":[{"name":"Adel","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]},{"name":"Adelle","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Adèle de Domart was born on 15 March 1202, in Domart-en-Ponthieu, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France. She married Gaucher DE BOUFFLERS about 1217, in Boufflers, Somme, Picardie, France. They were the parents of at least 3 daughters. She died in 1257, in Boufflers, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France, at the age of 55."},"et":{"15 March 1202–1257":"15. märts 1202–1257","1197–1248":"1197–1248","1197–Male":"1197–Surnud","1225–Female":"1225–Surnud","1218–Female":"1218–Surnud","1221–Female":"1221–Surnud","1225–1279":"1225–1279","1202–1257":"1202–1257","1248":"1248","1225":"1225","about 1217":"umbes 1217","1257":"1257","1202":"1202","1279":"1279","